Now that spring has officially sprung, and seeing that I’ll be enjoying my spring break from the comfort of my own home, I was in the mood for a festive and fruity smoothie bowl. I’ve been loving my powerful new Ninja® Foodi® Smoothie Bowl Maker and Nutrient Extractor* with smartTORQUE™ that allows me to blend everything together without stopping to stir, shake, or spatula! #SponsoredByNinja The built-in tamper blends and powers through frozen foods with less liquid for perfectly thick smoothie bowls. You can even flip it upside down it’s so thick! You’re going to love this tropical tasty treat and enjoy adding your favorite toppings to make an insta-worthy bowl! 

#NinjaFoodiBlender #NinjaFoodiFamily #smoothiebowl @ninjakitchen
 
Tangerine Mango Smoothie Bowl
Prep time 2 minutes
Ready in 5 minutes
Servings 1 large glass

Ingredients:
* 1/2 cup frozen mango 
* 1 cup frozen ripe banana 
* 1 peeled tangerine  
* 1 tbsp plant-based milk 
* ½ tsp vanilla extract (optional) 
* 1 drop agave (optional) 
* Toppings: Shredded coconut, granola, chia seeds, sliced mango, shaved almonds or any of your favorites! 

Directions:
1. Place everything in a blender and process until completely smooth. 
2. Top with your favorite toppings!

I absolutely love creating delicious meals with the help of my friends at @pathoflifebrand. Their pre-packaged quinoa, cauliflower, and rice blends provide the perfect base for a hearty dish that can be customized any way you like.  It takes so much of the guesswork out of preparing a meal when I don’t have as much time or energy. Their blends are always packed with flavor and high-quality ingredients that leave me satisfied. Today I am using the Cilantro Lime Rice Blend with added tempeh for protein to bring you a very tasty dish! Enjoy! #sponsored

Cilantro Lime Rice with Ginger Tempeh

Prep time: 10 minutes
Cook time: 15 minutes
Total time: 25 minutes
Yields 2 servings

Ingredients:

* 1 tablespoon of vegetable oil 
* ¼ cup of finely diced yellow onion 
* 2 garlic cloves, minced 
* 1 teaspoon of minced ginger 
* 1 (8-ounce) package of tempeh 
* 2 tablespoons of tamari sauce 
* 1 ½ tablespoon of lime juice (about half of a lime) 
* 1 teaspoon of a liquid sweetener (agave or maple syrup) 
* 1 (10-ounce) bag of Path of Life Cilantro Lime Rice Blend 
* Minced cilantro, for garnish (optional) 

1. In a large pan over medium-high heat, heat the oil. Add the onions, garlic, ginger, and saute for 1 minute. Using your fingers, crumble the tempeh directly into the pan, and saute for another 1 to 2 minutes, stirring regularly until the tempeh is lightly browned. 
2. Pour in the tamari sauce, lime juice, and your choice of a liquid sweetener, and stir until absorbed. Set aside. 
3. Cook the Path of Life Cilantro Lime Rice Blend according to the package instructions. Serve topped with crumbled tempeh, and with minced cilantro as garnish (if using).

node.title: Cilantro Lime Rice with Ginger Tempeh

Soup is my favorite go-to meal. The variety of possibilities are endless. With @frontiersoups it’s easier than ever to have a one-stop-shop that takes the guesswork out of cooking. Their incredible variety of mixes have everything you need to enjoy a hearty, healthy and full-flavored delicious meal again and again. It’s one of the easiest meals to make and offers the homemade taste and quality we all desire. 

Fall is my favorite time of year for soups and anytime is my favorite time for leftovers! This Frontier Soups™ West Coast Kale & Quinoa soup mix serves 8 so making this once for my husband and I produces four meals for us! Though it’s incredible on its own, these soup mixes are perfect for customizing as you like. I wanted to share my recipe with you where I added in some of my fall favorites like butternut squash, zucchini, corn kernels and kidney beans. It’s sure to be a new family favorite! Kale & Quinoa Soup

Ingredients:

* 1 tablespoon of oil 
* ½ of a medium yellow onion, diced 
* 3 garlic cloves, minced 
* ½ of a large zucchini, diced 
* 1 (12-ounce) package of frozen butternut squash 
* 1 (15-ounce) can of kidney beans, drained and rinsed 
* 1 (14-ounce) can of petite tomatoes, in their juices 
* 6 cups of vegetable broth 
* ½ cup of corn kernels  
* 1 (4.5-ounce) package of Frontier Soups Kale & Quinoa Soup Mix 
* Salt and pepper, to taste (optional) 

Directions:
1. In a large pot over medium-high heat, heat the oil. Add the onions and saute for about 5 minutes, until they’re translucent and tender. 
2. Add in the zucchini, butternut squash, kidney beans, tomatoes, vegetable broth, corn kernels, and Frontier Soups Kale & Quinoa Soup Mix. 
3. Bring the pot to a boil. Reduce the heat and simmer covered for 25 minutes, stirring occasionally. 
4. Turn off heat and allow it to stand for 10 minutes before serving.

I had a fabulous conversation with @mangomannutrition about @masteringdiabetes. I went in with hardly any knowledge about diabetes, and came out of our conversation feeling much more informed! Hope you give it a watch. And feel free to skip the first minute while I’m talking about my fuzzy pants and socks. 😂

Cyrus Khambatta has a degree in mechanical engineering from Stanford University as well as a PhD in nutritional biochemistry from UC Berkeley and has been living with type one diabetes since 2002. His book Mastering Diabetes is a NYT bestseller.

The family-owned @eatluckyfoods creates wholesome crafted Asian cuisine and delicious sauces like their Gochujang Korean chili pepper paste used in my new recipe. Their savory yet sweet sauce will make you fall in love with these mouthwatering Spicy Cauliflower Wings that you may or may not want to share!

Spicy Cauliflower Wings

Ingredients:

* ½ of a large head of cauliflower, cut into 1-inch florets 
* 1 tablespoon of sesame oil 
* ½ cup of all-purpose flour 
* 1 ½ teaspoon of sugar 
* 1 ½ teaspoon of ginger powder 
* 1 teaspoon of garlic powder 
* 1 teaspoon of onion powder 
* 3 tablespoons of soymilk 
* 2 teaspoon of soy sauce 
* 2 teaspoon of rice vinegar 
* 3 tablespoons of melted vegan butter 
* 1/4 cup of Lucky Foods Gochujang sauce 
* Sesame seeds, optional for garnish 
* Sliced green onion, optional for garnish 

Directions:

1. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F and line a baking sheet with a silicone mat or parchment paper. 
2. In a large bowl, toss the cauliflower florets with sesame oil and set aside. 
3. In a separate bowl, combine the flour, sugar, ginger powder, garlic powder, onion powder, soymilk, soy sauce, rice vinegar, and mix thoroughly. 
4. Add the flour paste to the large bowl and toss until the cauliflower is evenly coated.  
5. Place the coated cauliflower onto the prepared baking sheet and bake on the center rack for 30 minutes. 
6. While the cauliflower is baking, mix together the melted vegan butter and the Lucky Foods Gochujang sauce.  
7. Dip the baked cauliflower (after it cools a bit) into the sauce and then bake for another 15 minutes.

Having my own garden now, I really appreciate the fresh colorful array of vegetables and incorporating a wide variety into my meals as often as possible. Since so many people don’t have the space or time for a garden; finding quick, nutritious and flavorful meals can be a challenge. I am so thrilled to have discovered @frontiersoups and their incredible variety of ready-to-go mixes that provide multiple meals for such an affordable price in just minutes. While so many soup mixes on the market are high in sodium, @frontiersoups mixes have no added salt so you can personalize flavor to your liking. Their soup mixes are gluten-free and made with quality ingredients to nourish wellness and awaken taste buds. 

As I explore and enjoy some of their mouthwatering mixes, I’ll be sharing some of my creations with you starting with their flavor-packed Ohio Valley Vegetable Soup. This mix is so hearty on its own, but it’s incredibly versatile that you can add in anything you’d like or have on hand. I added more of a fall/winter twist by incorporating cabbage, zucchini and broccoli and threw in some firm diced tofu for protein. Enjoy! #sponsored

Ingredients:

* 1 package of Frontier Soups ™ Ohio Valley Vegetable Soup Mix 
* 2 tablespoons of olive oil 
* 1 medium yellow onion, diced 
* ½ medium zucchini, halved lengthwise and sliced 
* 1 cup of shredded cabbage 
* 1 cup of broccoli florets 
* ½ (16-ounce) package of extra firm tofu, diced 
* 8 cups of vegetable broth 
* 2 tablespoons of lemon juice 
* Salt and pepper, to taste 
* Hot sauce, optional 

Directions:
1. In a large pot over medium-high heat, heat the oil. Add the onions and saute for about 5 minutes, until they’re translucent and tender. 
2. Add in the zucchini, cabbage, broccoli florets, tofu, and vegetable broth. 
3. Bring the pot to a boil. Reduce the heat and simmer covered for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally. 
4. Stir in the contents of the pasta packet, and return to simmer covered for 20 minutes.  
5. Add lemon juice, salt, pepper, and hot sauce (if using), and continue to simmer for 2 to 3 minutes uncovered.

#LightlifePartner This plant-based chicken parmesan casserole with @lightlifefoods new Plant-Based Chicken Tenders from @sprouts gives you the gourmet feel without the gourmet price tag. The @lightlifefoods Plant-Based Chicken Tenders have a crispy breading with a juicy pull-apart texture that’s so good, I ate the rest of them while making the casserole! All the ingredients come together to make an incredibly creamy, comforting, classic dish. There’s nothing like throwing together an absolutely delicious meal in a matter of minutes. Here’s how you can too! 

Mix together your favorite pasta sauce and noodles in an 8x8 casserole dish. You know how saucy you like it - so trust your gut! Layer the @lightlifefoods Plant-Based Chicken Tenders on top, then drench it with your favorite plant-based cheese. (Or lightly sprinkled, again, whatever suits your fancy!). Pop in the oven at 350 degrees for 50 minutes and enjoy! #Lightlife

I wasn’t lying when I said I could live off of rice and beans for the rest of my life. I make this pot on a weekly basis. With a pressure cooker, it doesn’t require monitoring the stove or how much water is in the pot, you don’t have to soak the beans if you don’t feel like it, and they are absolutely delicious! The printable recipe link is in my stories. Please note that when I hit the sauté button, I do it with the lid off. I realized that’s not clear in the video, but it’s an important step because I like the water to evaporate.

When I’m feeling fancier, I cook them with a little onion, garlic, jalapeños, and a pinch of cumin. 😍 anyone else make beans from scratch? How do you do yours?

Have you tried @purefarmland’s plant-based line of burger and breakfast patties, meatballs, sausages and vegan ground beef? I love the convenience of locating these items in my mainstream grocery store and can’t get enough of the taste! Packed with protein and flavor, I had a hard time coming up with just one recipe to share with you! You will love this hearty, flavorful, beefy veggie dish over rice. It makes for a great weekday meal.

Ingredients: 
1 package of Pure Farmland plant-protein starters
½ of a yellow onion, diced
1 medium zucchini, diced
1 can of corn, drained
1 (8-ounce) can of tomato sauce
1 cup of water
Salt and pepper, to taste
Cooked brown rice (optional)

Directions:
Cook the Pure Farmland plant-protein starter with the onion and zucchini, according to the package instructions.
Pour in the can of corn, tomato sauce, water, salt, and pepper, and stir until everything is mixed. Bring to a boil, cover with a lid, and lower to a simmer for 20 minutes.
Serve over brown rice (optional).

Along time ago, I heard about freezing bananas as they started turning brown. So when my bananas started spotting, I threw them all in the fridge and when it came time to use them, they were totally frozen solid — peel and all. Unusable without being thawed first (which I didn’t have time for). 

This is how I do it now. You don’t have to slice them up if you don’t want to, but I used to have a weak blender that couldn’t break up frozen chunks, so I do it this way now out of habit. How do you freeze yours?

I have a guide for freezing bananas on the website: https://plantbasedonabudget.com/recipe/how-to-freeze-bananas/
